<paper id="1865562238"><title>Timed Modal Specification - Theory and Tools</title><year>1993</year><authors><author org="Chalmers University of Technology" id="621759795">Karlis Cerans</author><author org=", Aalborg University" id="1058126842">Jens Chr. Godskesen</author><author org=", Aalborg University" id="2146581609">Kim Guldstrand Larsen</author></authors><n_citation>58</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>3820865</reference><reference>130102441</reference><reference>1496019238</reference><reference>1503973138</reference><reference>1967761514</reference><reference>2011694130</reference><reference>2117519330</reference><reference>2138549619</reference><reference>2148106163</reference><reference>2153273838</reference><reference>2788739769</reference><reference>2914011863</reference></references><venue id="1162450063" type="C">Computer Aided Verification</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-56922-7_21</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.46733">Programming language</keyword><keyword weight="0.45119">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.45406">Generalization</keyword><keyword weight="0.46297">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.58788">Bisimulation</keyword><keyword weight="0.54563">Process calculus</keyword><keyword weight="0.52506">Modal</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>In this paper we present the theory of Timed Modal Specifications (TMS) together with its implementation, the tool Epsilon. TMS and Epsilon are timed extensions of respectively Modal Specifications [7, 9] and the Tav system [6, 4]. Also, the theory of TMS is an extension of real-timed process calculi with the specific aim of allowing loose or partial specifications. This allows us to define a notion of refinement, generalizing in a natural way the classical notion of bisimulation.</abstract></paper>